label.value: Allele-Specific Oligonucleotide Real-Time Quantitative Polymerase Chain Reaction

value.value: An application of real time PCR that is capable of detecting and quantifying a specific allelic version of a gene.
A test that uses electrical current conductance as measured through skin to help diagnose disease, most commonly lung tumors.

A collaborative process for the coordination of services for an individual undergoing some manner of treatment. This process includes assessment, planning, facilitation, care coordination, evaluation, and advocacy for options and services to meet the comprehensive health needs for the individual and their family.

label.value: Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy with Burst-Suppression

value.value: A neurological disorder characterized by recurring seizures presenting within the first three months of life, progressive cerebral dysfunction, and an EEG pattern of periods of low electrical brain activity interspersed with bursts of high spiky activity.
Any method to measure the number of dividing cells in a culture, or to measure the change in the proportion of cells that are dividing.
Methods to detect and examine metastatic cancer cells found in the peripheral blood.
The act, by a healthcare worker, of monitoring an identified subject and recording signs, symptoms, or behavior.
The act of decreasing both the temperature and blood flow to an organ or tissue for the purpose of preserving it for transplantation.
A surgical procedure during which the blood supply to an organ or tissue is interrupted and then later reestablished, while maintaining the organ at physiologic body temperature.
The use of a medically inactive substance or intervention in substitution for a drug or other medically active treatment.
An imaging technique that utilizes a radiolabeled sugar given intravenously to help define the size, shape, and location of a breast tumor.

label.value: Montanide ISA-51/Peptide 946-tetanus peptide conjugate melanoma vaccine

value.value: A type of nuclear medicine study that utilizes a radioactive tracer to identify possible tumors.

The use of skin electrodes to pass a low intensity, pulsed electrical current through the scalp and into the brain.  This procedure is used to treat a variety of illnesses including anxiety, depression, and chronic pain.
A method for functional brain mapping that applies electrical stimulation to the exposed cortex of a patient and marks the cortex according to patient response.
An imaging modality that adds the imaging of shear waves to a conventional ultrasound, allowing for a more detailed image, and an accurate measurement of tissue elasticity.
An ultrasound imaging technique that uses low amplitude, low frequency shear waves to find solid tumors within tissue.
The complete examination of an elderly individual, which includes a full valuation of the physical and cognitive conditions, as well as a check of the patient's emotional state.
The delivery of pharmacological agents to a brain tumor or resection cavity via specially placed catheters that bypass the blood brain barrier.
A procedure that uses both a curette and hyfrecator for treatment of various skin conditions, including basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell skin carcinoma, viral warts, and pyogenic granulomas.
The use of instruments to quantify the redness of the skin. This is done to measure differences in erythema over time in a single patient and to gauge the stability or progression of a skin disease.
An examination technique that uses fluorescent dye and a specialized camera to inspect blood flow in the retina and choroid.
Any clinical attention received following a diagnosis or treatment, with the specific purpose of monitoring that specific diagnosis or treatment.

label.value: Fourier Transform Ion Cyclotron Resonance Mass Spectrometry

value.value: A type of mass spectrometry that uses the cyclotron frequency of ions in a fixed magnetic field to determine their ionic mass-to-charge ratio.
The placement of a mesh tube anywhere within the gastrointestinal tract. It is used to keep the lumen open and free of obstruction.

A severe form of epilepsy that presents in early childhood and is characterized by frequent, prolonged febrile or myoclonic seizures that may progress to status epilepticus and poor development of language, motor, and socialization skills.
Slow, involuntary, and nonpurposeful writhing movements that usually affect the upper limbs.
Excessive movement.
Diminished movement.
This gene is involved in the regulation of neutrophil cathepsin G and mast cell chymase activity.

Human SERPINA3 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 14q32.1 and is approximately 33 kb in length. This allele, which encodes alpha-1-antichymotrypsin protein, plays a role in the negative regulation of the activity of both neutrophil cathepsin G and mast cell chymase. Mutation of the gene is associated with alpha-1-antichymotrypsin deficiency and occlusive cerebrovascular disease. Genetic polymorphisms may be associated with increased susceptibility to either Alzheimer disease or Parkinson disease.
Alpha-1-antichymotrypsin (423 aa, ~48 kDa) is encoded by the human SERPINA3 gene. This protein is involved in the inhibition of neutrophil cathepsin G and mast cell chymase proteolytic activity.

label.value: Montanide ISA-51/Peptide 946 melanoma vaccine/Tetanus peptide melanoma vaccine

value.value: This gene plays a role in the reduction of glutathione-disulfides and glutathione-conjugated proteins.
Human GLRX wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 5q14 and is approximately 72 kb in length. This allele, which encodes glutaredoxin-1 protein, is involved in cellular redox
Glutaredoxin-1 (106 aa, ~12 kDa) is encoded by the human GLRX gene. This protein plays a role in the reduction of glutathione conjugates.
A collection of blood into the space between the pia membrane and arachnoid membrane.
This gene is involved in DNA double-strand break repair.
A collection of blood between the dura mater and the brain.
Human LIG3 wild-type allele is located within 17q11.2-q12 and is approximately 25 kb in length. This allele, which encodes DNA ligase 3 protein, plays a role in DNA repair.
DNA ligase 3 (1009 aa, ~113 kDa) is encoded by the human LIG3 gene. This protein is involved in the repair of double-strand breaks in DNA.
A collection of blood into the space between the dura mater and the skull.
This gene plays a role in both DNA translesion synthesis and the mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint.

label.value: gp100 Antigen/HPV-16 E7(12-20) Peptide Vaccine/Montanide ISA-51

value.value: Human MAD2L2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 1p36 and is approximately 17 kb in length. This allele, which encodes mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint protein MAD2B, is involved in the mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint and the modulation of translesional DNA synthesis.
A collection of blood between the scalp and the skull periosteum.

label.value: Mitotic Spindle Assembly Checkpoint Protein MAD2B

value.value: Mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint protein MAD2B (211 aa, ~24 kDa) is encoded by the human MAD2L2 gene. This protein plays a role in DNA repair and the mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint.
A neurologic disorder characterized by frequently recurring myoclonic seizures and other seizure types presenting within the first months of life.
